  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_book_en_A.Concise.Introduction.to.Linear.Algebra,.Geza.Schay,.Birkhauser,.2012_page_194_9",
    "text": "Theorem 4.2.10. (The Linear Transformations from U to V Form a Vector Space, Which Is Isomorphic to Mm,n). Let L(U, V) denote the set of all linear transformations from an n-dimensional vector space U to an m-dimensional vector space V, and let A = (a1, a2,..., an) be an ordered basis for U, B = (b1, b2,..., bm) an ordered basis for V, and Ta, B the m xn matrix that represents any T E L(U, V) relative to these bases. Then",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12114536990469808,
      0.4578373012810999,
      0.8788546329584477,
      0.563988095333973
    ],
    "page": "book_en_A.Concise.Introduction.to.Linear.Algebra,.Geza.Schay,.Birkhauser,.2012_page_194",
    "order": 11
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_book_en_A.Concise.Introduction.to.Linear.Algebra,.Geza.Schay,.Birkhauser,.2012_page_194_10",
    "text": "L(U, V), together with addition and scalar multiple of transformations as in Definition 4.2.4, is a vector space.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.1211453680104251,
      0.5654069773525872,
      0.8788546130468442,
      0.6017441854453781
    ],
    "page": "book_en_A.Concise.Introduction.to.Linear.Algebra,.Geza.Schay,.Birkhauser,.2012_page_194",
    "order": 12
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_book_en_A.Concise.Introduction.to.Linear.Algebra,.Geza.Schay,.Birkhauser,.2012_page_194_11",
    "text": "The mapping M from L(U, V) to the vector space Mm,n of all m x n matrices\" given by M (T) = Ta, is linear and an isomorphism. Hence L(U, V) is mn-dimensional.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
